          "body": "Verses 8–9 describe the aftermath of God's arrow in a chain of consecutive clauses. The wounded enemy stumbles (*kashal*, v.8) — the root suggests moral as well as physical collapse. Their own tongue becomes the agent of their destruction (v.8b) — a fulfillment of Proverbs 12:13 and 18:7. All who see them shake their heads (*nadad*, v.8c) — a gesture of contemptuous dismissal in the ancient Near East (cf. Psalm 22:7; Job 16:4; Jeremiah 18:16). And then the radius widens: *all men will fear* (v.9a) — not the targeted few, but *kol-adam*, all humanity. The private conspiracy has produced public theology. Mankind will not merely observe; they will *proclaim* the work of God (*nagad*, v.9b) and *ponder* what He has done (*sakhal*, v.9c). *Sakhal* carries the sense of understanding wisely, of deriving insight from observation. God's judgment is not merely punitive — it is pedagogical. The execution of justice becomes a sermon to every generation who hears the account."
