          "title": "The righteous man's end — glad, sheltered, and glorying",
          "body": "The psalm's final verse (v.10) names three consecutive states of the righteous man after God's vindication: he is *glad* (*samach*), he *takes refuge* (*chasah*), and he *glories* (*halal*). This is not a slight escalation — it is a movement from interior response (gladness) to relational posture (sheltering in God) to public declaration (boasting in Him). *Halal* is the root of *hallelu-Yah* — to praise, to boast, to make noise about. The psalm that opened with complaint (*siach*, v.1) ends with *halal*. The same voice that asked God to hear a troubled outpouring is now exulting aloud in what God has done. Howard Hendricks observed that the lament psalms are not a spiritual failure to be transcended but a path to be traveled — they arrive at praise *by* passing through honest complaint, not by avoiding it. The righteous in v.10 are glad *in Yahweh* (the covenant name appears here for the first time in the psalm), sheltered *in Him*, and glorying — not in their own survival, not in the enemy's defeat, but in God Himself."
